The writing style is candid and vivacious, and captures the unbridled excitement of a young woman experiencing independence for the first time. She writes in great detail about her acquaintances and social life, all set against the backdrop of the closing months of WW1. Written from a very personal perspective, she records her meetings with soldiers but events such as the actual armistice are glossed over in passing. A rare and fascinating feature of this diary are the descriptions of people and events in the photograph albums 2001/090/2/2/1/2-3, which, taken together, enable a complete picture of Margaret\'s life to emerge.', '1917 - 1919', 'default', '1 volume', '1 hardbacked volume with c. 220 lined pages, around half of them have been written on in ink.', 3);

